Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law establishing administrative liability for violation of the time and procedure for payment of goods (work, services) in procurement for public and municipal needs.
The Act is intended to address the very acute problem of non-performance by customers in public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation where entrepreneurs could not receive payment under State and municipal contracts already executed was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Office of the Procurator-General of the Russian Federation to take special control of the problem.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unfair employers who entered into unfunded contracts, tried to evade their obligations to pay and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, 9,700 submissions have been made by the Public Prosecutor ' s Office in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, as a result of which 4,500 officials have been brought to disciplinary proceedings, 533 administrative officials have been prosecuted, 75 materials have been submitted to the investigative bodies for the conduct of procedural checks, and 46 criminal proceedings have been initiated.
As a result, more than 66 billion roubles were owed to entrepreneurs.
These huge amounts were not accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion-dollar contracts.
Many, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts have led to massive debts.
Here's the case.
The head of a small company won a competition for several million roubles in social transport services.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money due on time.
The result is an increasing financial comm of salary, tax, credit debts that would have led to bankruptcy had the entrepreneur not sought assistance from the prosecutor's office.
The problem has now been reduced as much as possible in a number of regions.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt on State and municipal contracts identified by the prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation was about 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to rise to critical levels, the Public Prosecutor ' s Office operates under a manual crisis management regime.
The Attorney-General personally holds field meetings with local authorities to deal with all violations discovered by prosecutors in a substantive manner and to remedy them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already taken place in Jaroslavla and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of Federal Act No. 189-FZ "On the amendment of the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation with regard to the establishment of administrative liability of the employer's officials for violation of the time and procedure for the payment of goods (work and services) in procurement to meet State and municipal needs", which was signed last week by the President of the Russian Federation, will improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was prepared by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Office of the Procurator-General.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences with an article which provides for a fine of between 30,000 and 50,000 roubles for breaching the terms and procedure of payment of goods, works and services by the employer ' s official in State and municipal procurement.
If an official has already been subject to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he or she will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure that these legislative innovations are applied in practice.
