Judges are asked to protect themselves from presidents.
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (CHR), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes that the powers of the presidents of the courts be limited and that their election be established.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the Human Rights Council wishes to introduce special districts that will not be attached to the administrative and territorial branch of the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit proposals in the context of the presidential commission.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on 3 January 2017, which was given by the President after a meeting with the members of the Council.
At a meeting with members of the Council on 8 December 2016, some cases of judicial arbitrariness were discussed, as well as the problems of public control in places of detention (see JO of 9 December).
The outcome of the HRC ' s work was 25 proposals, both concerning the independence of the judiciary and the detection of miscarriages of justice, as well as the financing of the courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presiding officers of the courts in order to enhance the independence of the remaining judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and has received the support of the judicial community, the President of the Court, in the opinion of the HRC, should present him for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now permits.
It is also proposed that the President be denied the right to allocate cases to judges.
This is something that experts allow to do, a specially written computer program can do.
The HRC also considers that the President is not entitled to "predict the judge's qualifications, initiate disciplinary action against him or her, and decide on additional material payments".
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to "the election of the Presidents of the Courts by the judges themselves" and "to give them powers for a relatively short period of time, with mandatory rotation".
All presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are now appointed by the President for a period of six years, on the proposal of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from the regional administrations, the HRC proposes to re-organize appeals and cassation in the ordinary courts.
Their structure is now linked to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that "it is necessary to ensure that individual courts of appeal and cassation are organized not at the level of the regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts".
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitral tribunals.
They have "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who are hampered by the use of "telephone law".
HRC justices of the peace propose that the people's jurors be strengthened to deal with certain "civil and administrative cases" with their participation.
For example, deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement, protection of honour and dignity, deprivation of driving rights, etc.
"It's just our proposals," explained the JO member of the HRC, a judge of the Constitutional Court retired Tamar Morshakov.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate applied not only to the HRC but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the Armed Forces to carry out the task (the co-perpetrators are the Gender Procurator and the Human Rights Commissioner in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on the effectiveness of the Russian Federation ' s independence of justice, the Chairman of the Armed Forces of Vyacheslav Lebedev is due before 1 September.
Living a tall life: semi-elegance and clever designers turned this little apartment in Earl's Court into a spacious home.
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious house in Nightsbridge to an apartment in Earl's Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a nice, modeled Anna-style house, and the new design says that Joan didn't pack her things and move again.
"I used to live with my ex in Nightsbridge in a much larger area," Joan says.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earl's Court, and there were just as high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered a price on the same day."
Since the first review, a 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Initially, it was an apartment with one bedroom of complex planning – to get into the bedroom, it had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add space to store things and semi-estate to squeeze the maximum benefit from the generous ceiling height.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands," she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill architectural design studio "Duck & Shed" to use the 12.5-foot ceiling and create a housing that would not only be a successful project but would be good for Joan.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a semi-estate where one could stand at full growth.
Erfan had to think creatively to deal with the briff.
"The work with steel structures is very complicated," he explains.
"We had to set up rooms so that they could be placed above each other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was not just necessary to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allow the use of the spaces from above and from below."
This decision allowed Erfan to have two full-sized rooms one above the other in the space to be occupied – and a lot more interesting.
From the semi-ethage through the vintage copper light window of "Retrouvius", a view of the gorgeous living room below is opened.
Mirror furniture with gold trim, silver accents, and vintage lighting devices from Serge Mui are setting up the design style.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding sight, spaciousness, and light.
The short corridor is covered with mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror panel looks like a window to another room.
At the entrance, the mirror cabinets serve to store all of Joan's dishes.
In order to create a sense of greater luxury, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when it is not used.
There's nothing new in the emerging kitchens.
The unique thing about this kitchen is that it's a moving door upstairs, like in a garage.
"The art of engineering was involved here," Ehrfan tells us about a reinforced steel wood-fibre shield door.
"It's equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slips very easily."
Thanks to the prudent use of space and storage areas, Joan received an additional 16 square metres, an additional bedroom, and an improved layout.
"In the end, the floor area is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your real estate is valued on," says Erfan.
"Breakingly speaking, the real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area."
Here, they were able to increase the floor area by using quality materials that gave luxury space.
"The materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to the house," says Erfan.
"No one falls in love with the wiring in the walls.
It is important, but it does not touch the strings of our hearts."
It's a sign that, at the expense of a good design and an enlarged meter, an apartment can turn from something normal to something amazing.
Actually, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
The Government approved the establishment of a cultural policy commission
The Russian Government has approved the establishment of a commission on State cultural policy.
The relevant decree has been published on the Government ' s website.
According to the document, the main task of the commission will be to formulate and adjust strategic approaches to cultural policy implementation.
The Commission will also draft a cultural policy strategy, clarify tasks and prepare new programmes for its implementation.
The head of the Commission has been appointed Vice-President of the Government of the Russian Federation.
The composition of the commission will be approved separately.
The Prime Minister of the Russian Federation, Dmitry Medvedev, approved in 2016 a plan for the implementation of the State cultural policy strategy until 2030.
The plan includes 193 measures and measures to increase the influence of Russian culture in other countries, preserve a single cultural space and cultural heritage, and will contribute to the creation of conditions for the development of culture in the country.
