The brothers are fighting for a real estate empire worth more than $500 million.
Two brothers are fighting for one of Victoria's largest real estate empires, worth more than $500 million, 40 years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former director of Carlton's football club and developer Colin de Lutes live in Turak Palace three doors from his younger brother Paul, who sued him in the Supreme Court for the division of property and assets.
Paul wants to leave the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is still in a violent dispute about divorce.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, bought since their family bought a shop on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's property list includes office buildings today, building sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Golden Bank and Mount Buller, and shopping centres in the suburbs.
In agreement with Colin's late father, whom Paul describes as "the main driving force and dominant person" of the De Lutes family, he owns about two thirds of the company's assets and Paul owns about one third.
According to the court, Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's 176 million.
The division of property and money has become a stumbling block for Paul.
"The division offered by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property," he wrote in his first statement in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful reconciliation attempts, the first hearings of the Supreme Court were held.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business - from which Paul believes Colin has ruled it out.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of certain objects.
In Colin's testimony at the beginning of the trial, he says he looks forward to a resolution of the dispute.
"My Italian roots make me consider my family a top priority," he wrote.
Court costs are rising as a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, e-mails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Kramer have been added to the case; both parties have engaged the best-known lawyers, including King's Counsel Allan Meyers, and the best cooks.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late wife Luigi were immigrants from Italy; since the late 1950s, they had run dairy bars and gastronoms, and in the early 1970s they bought a shop in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last grade of school, and Paul was then a boy (about 10 years old).
Anna De Lutis says that he and Luigi, who died in 2012, were hoping to transfer their possessions to their sons without conflict.
"Louigi often told me he didn't want his brothers to go to court," she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of De Lutis' group of companies; Colina says that Mark got 10 million when he left the business and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "displeased with the financial conditions of their office".
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the AFL board of directors and, according to Eddie McGir's 2015 biography, the best friend of the TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin replied, a text message stating that, since the case had not yet been tried, "I really have nothing to say".
"I'm very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to sue me and talk in court about our family's name," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin testified that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father wouldn't want to see Paul and I arguing in court," he said, adding that "we still hope to resolve the conflict."
Friday, that hope seems to have been dispelled.
"Our case will soon be decided by a court of law," said Colin.
The new head of Trump's office is planning to limit the flow of information to the President.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
Then he'll be the first.
Politicalo reports that the new head of the White House is planning to limit the flow of information coming to President Trump, including news reports from the media, hoping to keep the Chief calm.
That's what reporter Josh Dawsey says.
"At a meeting held by the new Chief of the White House, John F. Kelly, with the management of the apparatus on his first working day, he identified the main problem in the White House under President Donald Trump, which he hopes to solve: bad channels of information to the President."
Kelly told the staff that the information had to go through it -- paper or briefings -- because the president would be better off making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is completely correct, but others have already failed in their attempt to subdue Trump by tracking the flow of information to him.
President Trump's relationship with television began decades ago - and now that he's in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
"When Trump, as a candidate, resented the unfair coverage of the campaign, it was useful to show him that he had received fair coverage in publications that could have been re-converted," said Sam Nanberg, a former adviser to the electoral staff in February.
Tara Palmery then wrote in "Policio" that "in the words of six former electoral staff members, in order to control Trump's habit of tweeting, it was necessary to make sure that the information received in person contained a constant stream of praise."
Okay.
But the idea that Trump's habit of tweeting has ever been "controlled" is ridiculous.
Maybe these election staff members know something we don't know -- for example, if it weren't for them, Trump's tweet would have been even more provocative.
We may never find out about the tweets Trump hasn't published.
If his staff kept him out of trouble at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has ever been able to keep Trump from pouring oil into the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to push their subpoena by giving Trump material - reliable or not - that confirms their views.
"Politico"--this is exactly the story-- wrote in May about the counselor's tendency to constantly give the president questionable information.
Here's an example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"The current and former Trump employees say Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
This happened at the end of February, when someone printed out an article from GotNews.com to the president, Charles C. Johnson's Internet proprietor's website, where Katie Welsch's deputy chief of staff was accused of being behind the leaks in the White House.
It doesn't matter that Johnson's been forever booked on Twitter for aggressive behavior, that he hasn't presented specific facts, or that in the past he's launched false accusations and then abandoned them.
Trump read the article and started asking staff about Welch."
Goldmacher adds that then Chief of Staff Rains Pribus and Secretary of the Rob Porter machine "tryed to build a system to manage and document the flow of the paper that Trump receives."
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly's trying to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Pribus, but Trump still has impulsive nature, and his associates are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
The Tumen Prosecutor ' s Office is fighting an HIV dissident.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office challenged the decision of the Kalinin Ra ' isud Tümeni, who had dropped the criminal case against a local woman whose daughter had died of HIV.
As a result, the child is said to have died because the mother is an HIV-dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court relieved her of her responsibility for reconciliation with the injured father.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished without setting a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against a woman resident of Tümena was brought under article 109, paragraph 1, of the Criminal Code (causing death by negligence) in April, after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection.
According to the Public Prosecutor ' s Office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV did not exist," explained in the Prosecutor's Office of the Tumen Region.
The criminal case was brought to Kalininsk Raisud Tümeni, who decided on 25 July to discontinue it.
The father of the girl who died made a request to do so, explaining that "he has asked his wife, has no claims against her, has made amends and has apologized".
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office did not agree with the court ' s decision and appealed, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be reversed and referred to a new hearing.
The girl died, and it's impossible to make amends for the crime.
The HIV-positive mother refused to examine the baby and treat her with a dangerous infection, as recommended by the doctors," reported to the Public Prosecutor's Office.
In the view of the oversight body, she should be punished, otherwise her example would be followed by other HIV-dissidents.
According to the Tumen AIDS Centre, there are now about 12 HIV-positive children in Tumen province who are not receiving medical care because of their parents' refusal.
"This situation has already improved - during the year of the work of the special group, half of the parents who have categorically refused to treat children for HIV, changed their minds - allowed for diagnosis, started taking medications," said Elena Losewa, spokesperson of the AIDS Centre.
According to her, it was impossible to influence parents by law and not all HIV-positive children could be identified - mothers were not allowed to examine them, were hiding, and were running away with children from hospitals.
What are the dangers of HIV dissidents?
At the end of last year, Peterburg social scientists presented the results of Russia's first study of the so-called HIV dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are called people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Health professionals and AIDS service activists in the NPOs call such views anti-medical, and they see their dissemination as a serious threat.
