The Prosecutor read out the statements of Roy Lynn Roy's mother saying: "It has not been a day since I mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I do it - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever," he says.
Sister Roy Kamdin Roy said that she was obsessed with the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"The man who's been with me ever since I was born is the pain that stays with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to set a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that provides for responsibility for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with carbon monoxide poisoning symptoms, Carter was 17 years old.
The case drew the attention of the entire country when it became known that he had been pushed into Carter's suicide message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don't know, there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before he died while he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before she committed suicide, she wrote, "You have to do it, Conrad," and, "You just have to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted attention with Roy's death, and he banned her from talking to the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
