Create a novel comic book: One castle in English history
In the recent past, Scotty's tiny castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s served as a refuge for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy spot in the Bul River Valley in Kent County, he's been watching a stormy story around, and now he's inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire with a cop hair, and a history-oriented, romantic comic book.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says with enthusiasm.
"You feel that way in person when you hold this letter in your hand."
The Castle in England covers a period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells about families who lived in Scotty; each story was illustrated by a young British artist, Isaac Lenkevich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book, based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "Dead Man's Tooths and Other Storys", a collection of British Library documents; this project suddenly touched him to the depths of his heart.
"I could have been touched by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites," he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days the lights were lit.
And 300 years later, in the future, you feel like you're there, too.
Ah, I love archives!"
For a man so passionate about old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in a castle for four months ("in truth, I've been a bit of a guest there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the "new" Victorian castle all day, went through the archives and looked at the many treasures of the estate and old things -- for example, the heads of hyenas on walls or bottles that had been lying in a pit for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to the foresters, gardeners, and sometimes artists working on illustrations of his book.
Then at night, he "drank whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scotty's castle is not well understood, because the National Foundation did not have full access to it until 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff were just starting to deal with the archive he described as "what the aristocrats have been putting on the attic for centuries".
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what, "You think that land disputes are boring," Rhodes says, but there were two families fighting for this beret.
That's what happens, guys!"
In some stories, the castle collection is becoming the starting point for broader research in English history: for example, in Workman, the hero is leaving the castle just built to join the 1381 Rural Revolution.
"There is information about the riot that took place at the castle in 1380, in a book called Knight's Families of Kent and Sussex," Rhodes says.
"The Christian rebellion began in these places, and I thought the riot was a good start.
Maybe they were connected."
Other stories are strongly linked to the castle's history - for example, the priest, who talks about the Jesuit priest who the Darrell family has been hiding for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Contrabandist," about an 18th-century smuggler, Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (which was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family of all Scotty's: "Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect cheater, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women--I imagine them as a company of cute guys who can look after the heirs of great fortunes."
After working at the Castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish middle of nowhere, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elymanmäki, a place where he was a sanatorium at the beginning of the twentieth century, and then it came back to the forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like this, damn it, I have to go back to real life."
