Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease the WRC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered nightmares for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests otherwise: diets rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate the symptoms of those suffering from inflammable intestinal diseases.
It is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leading to colicks and swelling of the stomach, chronic or bloody insanity, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
In order to mitigate the symptoms, patients are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at Washington University have found that the main amino acid protein triptophane contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells in the intestines ensure that harmful germs from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering an inflammation process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance while protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severe for inflammation, it can lead to inflammable intestinal diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacteria in their intestines have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs a triptofan -- one of the building elements of the protein -- to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We've established a connection between one type of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of a normal microbioma of the bowel, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptofane was kept in mice, the more immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for people: a combination of L. reuteri and a rich triptofan diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammable environment in the intestine.
The post-mortem Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganwas, studying a variety of immune cell tolerance groups, found that one group of test mice had these cells and another group, which belonged to the same line but was separate, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by microbiomas in the intestines of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses, and mushrooms that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestinal cells of the mice was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells but missing in mice without them.
Mice raised in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiom and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and they developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in the liquid environment and then transferred small portions of the liquid, without bacteria, to unformed immune cells separated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it was a by-product of triptofane, known as indol-3-milk acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of triptofane in mice' food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of triptofane was halved, the number of cells also doubled.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people have the same tolerance cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether by-products of triptofane from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans as much as in mice, but in humans suffering from inflammable intestinal diseases, defects in genes associated with triptofan have been detected.
She says, "Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because these cells are responsible for inflammation processes on the inside of the intestines.
High levels of triptofane, if L. reuteri is available, can potentially lead to an increase in their population."
