There will be two new territories in Russia, Abaza and Novotroitsk, which are more advanced in economic and social development.
The relevant decisions of the Government of the Russian Federation will enter into force today, 4 August.
The boundaries and economic activities of the TORA on the territory of the city of Abaza in the Republic of Hakassia have been defined.
In a city with 15,000 inhabitants, there will be a special legal business regime, as well as a minimum capital investment by residents, with a minimum number of new permanent jobs.
This is expected to attract about 2.5 billion roubles of investment into the city, as well as more than 600 new jobs.
The list of economic activities in which the TOR Abaza will have a special legal business regime, such as crop production, livestock production, food production, non-alcoholic beverages and clothing.
The Government of the Republic has already signed framework agreements for the implementation of eight investment projects.
There are also plans to reduce the Territory's dependence on the Abakan mine's city-forming plant.
In January 2017, the authorities in the region reported that Hakasia had fulfilled all the terms of Mineconomy for the creation of a TOR.
The authorities in the Orenburg region have done likewise.
There, the city of Novotroitsk will also establish a territory that is ahead of socio-economic development.
This will allow for the diversification of the monocity economy, the reduction of its dependence on the U.S. steel industry, and the creation of more than 2,300 jobs and investment of more than 8 billion roubles.
The list of economic activities in which the new TOR will have a special legal regime for entrepreneurs includes, inter alia, freshwater fish farming, feed production, medicines and medical supplies.
Novotroitsky was the first of the monocities in the Orenburg region to become a Tor.
Let us recall that the area of advanced development is an economic zone with favourable tax conditions, simplified administrative procedures and other privileges, which is being created to attract investment in improving the lives of the population.
Among the benefits for residents, SAR can be identified as: a profit tax of not more than 5 per cent for the first five years and not less than 10 per cent for the next five years, social contributions of 7.6 per cent for 10 years, the use of a free customs area, preferential access to various infrastructure facilities, and concessional rent rates.
